# Privacy Diff — Cursor

## Core stack (required)

| System | Location | Role |
|--------|----------|------|
| Superpowers | `vendor/superpowers/`, `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json` | Workflow engine — default for every task |
| Agency Agents | `vendor/agency-agents/`, rules `agency-*.mdc` in `.cursor/rules/` | Specialist execution — default for every task |

If `vendor/` or `.cursor-plugin/` is missing, run `npx ai-dev-setup init` without `--skip-vendor`.

## Pointers (do not duplicate)

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `.ai/rules.md` | Engineering principles (SOLID, DRY, KISS, YAGNI), anti-patterns, layer rules |
| `.ai/workflow.md` | Lifecycle, TDD, review checklist |
| `.ai/agents.md` | Specialist activation + quality expectations per role |
| `docs/CONVENTIONS.md` | Stack-specific patterns: layer separation, constants, input validation |
| `docs/API-PATTERNS.md` | HTTP layer responsibilities + validation contract — load on every API task |
| `docs/*` | Other deep references—load only when relevant |

## Project facts

- Language: Javascript, Typescript — Framework: Next.js — DB: PostgreSQL
- Commands: `npm run test` · `npm run lint` · `npm run build`

## Behavior

- Answer briefly; cite paths instead of pasting large files
- Prefer existing patterns in-repo over generic tutorials
- After architectural change, update `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` in the same change when behavior crosses modules
- **Superpowers subagents / Task workers:** process comes from Superpowers; **implementation** workers still load the **Agency** role from `agency-*.mdc` / `.ai/agents.md` (plan-named role or mapped specialist)—not a generic implementer when Agency applies

## Rules layout

- `core-rules.mdc` — always on (keep lean)
- `routing.mdc` — always on; Superpowers + Agency are the default for all tasks
- `workflow.mdc`, `review.mdc`, `agents.mdc` — task-shaped detail (still follow defaults in `routing.mdc`)
- `agency-*.mdc` — Agency specialist rules (on demand)
